{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"91a0784d-5988-43e1-9aae-cf0366d84877","content":"No project found at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command: \"dotnet\"`** with `\"run\"` in `args` builds and launches your server.\n- Your MCP server must read JSON-RPC messages from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout**. Make sure any logging goes to **stderr**, not stdout.\n- After saving, open the Command Palette → **MCP: List Servers** to verify it's detected.\n\nIf you publish your server as a standalone executable instead, replace the command/args with the path to the built binary directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"658de0e8-c86c-441a-818c-8a570657f0f0","outputTokens":289,"requestId":"5C35:1C6615:1CDE2F3:1FFCFB6:69FA936A"},"id":"0001c2e2-a222-4df8-93f9-fb0975074ab0","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:03:45.674Z","parentId":"af993b03-f981-4192-82c5-5d0416eb7dd5"}
